---

## Critical Issues

**[WorkspaceItem.tsx:112] React Rules of Hooks violation — `useUnreadStore` called after a conditional `return`**

The component has an early return at line 52 (`if (isInitializing) return (...)`). The `useUnreadStore` selector is called at line 112, which is below that return. Hooks must be called unconditionally on every render. The comment at line 45 ("Hooks must be called unconditionally") only covers `useWorkingDuration`; whoever added `useUnreadStore` missed the existing early return.

Fix: move the `useUnreadStore` call above the `if (isInitializing)` block, alongside `useWorkingDuration`:

```tsx
const sessionId = workspace.current_session_id;
const hasUnseenActivity = useUnreadStore(
  (s) => !!sessionId && !!s.unreadSessionIds[sessionId]
);

if (isInitializing) {
  // ...
  return (...);
}
```

---

## Warnings

**[status.ts:162-163, 192, 218, 247] `sortByStatusPriority`, `getStatusCounts`, `getRepoPriorityStatus`, and `groupByStatus` ignore `hasUnseenActivity`**

These four functions call `getDisplayStatus(workspace)` with no second argument, so they always get `false` for `hasUnseenActivity`. The consequences are:

1. `sortByStatusPriority` — sidebar workspace ordering never promotes a "Done" session that has unseen activity. An unread workspace sorts to the bottom alongside idle ones.
2. `getRepoPriorityStatus` — collapsed repo badge color never shows amber for an unread-but-idle session. The repo looks idle even though one of its workspaces has a dot.
3. `getStatusCounts` / `groupByStatus` — if these are ever used to render a grouped sidebar, the "unread" bucket will be under-counted.

The `hasUnseenActivity` flag is frontend-only (in Zustand, not in the `Workspace` type), so these pure utility functions can't receive it directly. The fix is to add an optional `unreadSessionIds: Set<string>` parameter to each function and derive the flag internally:

```ts
export function sortByStatusPriority<T extends Workspace>(
  workspaces: T[],
  unreadSessionIds?: Set<string>
): T[] {
  return [...workspaces].sort((a, b) => {
    const hasUnreadA = !!(a.current_session_id && unreadSessionIds?.has(a.current_session_id));
    const hasUnreadB = !!(b.current_session_id && unreadSessionIds?.has(b.current_session_id));
    const statusA = getDisplayStatus(a, hasUnreadA);
    // ...
  });
}
```

`RepositoryItem.tsx` would read the store once and pass it down. Alternatively, `RepositoryItem` could derive `unreadSessionIds` from the store before calling `sortByStatusPriority`. Either way, the store must be consulted at the call site.

---

**[ChatArea.tsx:66] Full unread map subscription causes cross-workspace re-renders**

```ts
const unreadMap = useUnreadStore((s) => s.unreadSessionIds);
```

This subscribes to the entire `unreadSessionIds` object. Whenever any session in any workspace is marked read or unread (including sessions from workspaces the user hasn't opened), `ChatArea` re-renders and recomputes the `useMemo` below it.

Fix: derive a stable selector scoped to the sessions in this workspace's tabs:

```ts
const chatSessionIdSet = useMemo(() => new Set(chatSessionIds), [chatSessionIds]);
const unreadSessionIds = useUnreadStore(
  useShallow((s) => {
    const ids = new Set<string>();
    for (const sid of chatSessionIdSet) {
      if (s.unreadSessionIds[sid]) ids.add(sid);
    }
    return ids;
  })
);
```

Note that `useShallow` alone won't help here because the derived `Set` is a new reference each time — you'd need to either store the result as an array for shallow comparison, or use a ref-based memoization approach. The simplest correct fix is to keep the current `useMemo` but narrow the subscription to only check `chatSessionIds`:

```ts
const unreadMap = useUnreadStore(
  useShallow((s) => {
    const relevant: Record<string, true> = {};
    for (const sid of chatSessionIds) {
      if (s.unreadSessionIds[sid]) relevant[sid] = true;
    }
    return relevant;
  })
);
```

`useShallow` from zustand will prevent re-renders when the filtered subset hasn't changed.

---

**[ChatArea.tsx:76-81] `markRead` only fires on `activeSessionId` change, misses the initial mount**

```ts
const activeSessionId = activeTab?.data?.sessionId;
useEffect(() => {
  if (activeSessionId) {
    unreadActions.markRead(activeSessionId);
  }
}, [activeSessionId]);
```

When a user has a workspace already open and the agent finishes (marking the session unread), then switches to a different workspace and switches back, `activeSessionId` does not change — it was already set before the unread was marked. The `useEffect` does not re-fire because the dependency hasn't changed. The tab dot will linger until the user switches away and back.

Fix: add a second read path. The simplest is to also call `markRead` on the `unreadMap` subscription itself when the active session is in the unread set. Alternatively, call `markRead` in the tab click handler `handleTabChange` before (or after) `onTabChange` is called, which is always invoked when a tab becomes active through user interaction. The effect handles the initial-mount case; the click handler handles the "already here when notification arrived" case.

---

**[MainLayout.tsx:338-347] `handleWorkspaceClick` marks only `current_session_id` as read, misses tabs with different sessions**

```ts
if (workspace.current_session_id) {
  unreadActions.markRead(workspace.current_session_id);
}
```

A workspace can have multiple chat tabs, each bound to a different session (visible in the `chatTabSessionIds` array in the layout store). Clicking the workspace in the sidebar marks only the workspace's canonical `current_session_id` as read. If the user has a non-current session open in another tab that finished while the user was away, the tab dot on that tab will persist even after clicking into the workspace.

Fix: read `workspaceLayoutActions.getLayout(workspace.id).chatTabSessionIds` and mark all of them read on workspace click, since opening the workspace transitions the user into a context where they can see all tabs:

```ts
const handleWorkspaceClick = useCallback((workspace: Workspace) => {
  selectWorkspace(workspace.id);
  const layout = workspaceLayoutActions.getLayout(workspace.id);
  const allSessionIds = layout.chatTabSessionIds.length
    ? layout.chatTabSessionIds
    : workspace.current_session_id
      ? [workspace.current_session_id]
      : [];
  allSessionIds.forEach(unreadActions.markRead);
}, [selectWorkspace]);
```

---

## Suggestions

**[unreadStore.ts] localStorage accumulates orphaned session IDs indefinitely**

The persisted store is never pruned. Sessions from deleted or archived workspaces leave their IDs in localStorage forever. This is cosmetically harmless (keys are ~36 bytes each), but over months of use across many workspaces it becomes noise in storage. Consider adding a `pruneStale(knownSessionIds: string[])` action and calling it from the workspaces WS subscription handler (in `useGlobalSessionNotifications` or wherever the workspace list is consumed) to remove IDs that no longer correspond to any known session.

**[useGlobalSessionNotifications.ts:117-124] "working" state is assumed before first WS push**

`prevStatusMap` starts empty. The first time the WS pushes a workspace with `session_status = "idle"`, `prevStatus` is `undefined`, so the condition `prevStatus && prevStatus !== status` is false and no unread is marked. This is correct behavior. However, if the app loads and a session is already in `needs_response` state, `prevStatus` is `undefined` on the first push, so the transition is never detected. The session will never be marked unread in this launch. This is an acceptable trade-off (the existing `getDisplayStatus` logic already shows `needs_response` as "unread" in the sidebar via server-state), but it means the tab dot in `MainContentTabBar` will not show on a cold start if the session was waiting for input before the app launched.

**[status.ts:138] `needs_response` / `needs_plan_response` always map to `"unread"` regardless of the store**

The `getDisplayStatus` function unconditionally maps these two statuses to `"unread"`, which is correct. But the `hasUnseenActivity` parameter is only checked for the `idle` case (line 140). The implication is that for `needs_response` sessions, `markRead` in `ChatArea` and `MainLayout` will remove the indicator from the persisted store — but the sidebar will still show "unread" because the server-state status is still `needs_response`. This is actually the correct behavior (the agent still needs input), but it means `isUnread(sessionId)` from the store will return `false` while the sidebar shows "unread". These two data sources can diverge, which is fine since they represent different things (seen vs. actionable). Worth a comment to document this intentional divergence so the next developer doesn't try to "fix" it.

